ed by this collection. Shakespeare and Spenser: Attractive opposites presents new approaches, heralding a resurgence of interest in the relations between two of the greatest Renaissance English poets to a wider scholarly group and in a more systematic manner than before. This will be of interest to Students and academics interested in Renaissance literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aEnglish poets.  aRenaissance literature.  aRenaissance.  aShakespeare.  aSpenser.  alinguistic borrowings.  aresurgence of interest.1 aAnderson, Judith H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheney, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHays, Michael L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHile, Rachel E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorton, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLethbridge, J. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOldrieve, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrescott, Anne Lake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779176440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791764/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-